events.description: Ferdowsi completes his epic poem Shahnameh.

events.description: Battle of Hausbergen between bourgeois militias and the army of the bishop of Strasbourg.
events.html: • 1262 – Battle of Hausbergen between bourgeois militias and the army of the bishop of Strasbourg.[3]

events.description: The city of Pori (Swedish: Björneborg) is founded by Duke John on the shores of the Gulf of Bothnia.
events.html: • 1558 – The city of Pori (Swedish: Björneborg) is founded by Duke John on the shores of the Gulf of Bothnia.[4]

events.description: Treaty of Roskilde: After a devastating defeat in the Northern Wars (1655–1661), Frederick III, the King of Denmark–Norway is forced to give up nearly half his territory to Sweden.
events.html: • 1658 – Treaty of Roskilde: After a devastating defeat in the Northern Wars (1655–1661), Frederick III, the King of Denmark–Norway is forced to give up nearly half his territory to Sweden.[5]

events.description: Queen Anne, the younger sister of Mary II, becomes Queen regnant of England, Scotland, and Ireland.
events.html: • 1702 – Queen Anne, the younger sister of Mary II, becomes Queen regnant of England, Scotland, and Ireland.[6]

events.description: The Safavid Empire of Iran is defeated by an army from Afghanistan at the Battle of Gulnabad.
events.html: • 1722 – The Safavid Empire of Iran is defeated by an army from Afghanistan at the Battle of Gulnabad.[7]

events.description: Nader Shah, founder of the Afsharid dynasty, is crowned Shah of Iran.
events.html: • 1736 – Nader Shah, founder of the Afsharid dynasty, is crowned Shah of Iran.[8]

events.description: An anonymous writer, thought by some to be Thomas Paine, publishes "African Slavery in America", the first article in the American colonies calling for the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery.
events.html: • 1775 – An anonymous writer, thought by some to be Thomas Paine, publishes "African Slavery in America", the first article in the American colonies calling for the emancipation of slaves and the abolition of slavery.[9]

events.description: Gnadenhutten massacre: Ninety-six Native Americans in Gnadenhutten, Ohio, who had converted to Christianity, are killed by Pennsylvania militiamen in retaliation for raids carried out by other Indian tribes.
events.html: • 1782 – Gnadenhutten massacre: Ninety-six Native Americans in Gnadenhutten, Ohio, who had converted to Christianity, are killed by Pennsylvania militiamen in retaliation for raids carried out by other Indian tribes.[10]

entities.name: Native Americans in the United States

events.description: War of the Second Coalition: At the Battle of Abukir, a British force under Sir Ralph Abercromby lands in Egypt with the aim of ending the French campaign in Egypt and Syria.
events.html: • 1801 – War of the Second Coalition: At the Battle of Abukir, a British force under Sir Ralph Abercromby lands in Egypt with the aim of ending the French campaign in Egypt and Syria.[11]

entities.name: French campaign in Egypt and Syria

events.description: King Oscar I ascends to the thrones of Sweden and Norway.
events.html: • 1844 – King Oscar I ascends to the thrones of Sweden and Norway.[12]

events.description: The Althing, the parliament of Iceland, was reopened after 45 years of closure.
events.html: • 1844 – The Althing, the parliament of Iceland, was reopened after 45 years of closure.[13]

events.description: Sakai incident: Japanese samurai kill 11 French sailors in the port of Sakai, Osaka.
events.html: • 1868 – Sakai incident: Japanese samurai kill 11 French sailors in the port of Sakai, Osaka.[14]

events.description: French aviator Raymonde de Laroche becomes the first woman to receive a pilot's license.
events.html: • 1910 – French aviator Raymonde de Laroche becomes the first woman to receive a pilot's license.[15]

events.description: World War I: A British force unsuccessfully attempts to relieve the siege of Kut (present-day Iraq) in the Battle of Dujaila.
events.html: • 1916 – World War I: A British force unsuccessfully attempts to relieve the siege of Kut (present-day Iraq) in the Battle of Dujaila.[16]

events.description: International Women's Day protests in Petrograd mark the beginning of the February Revolution (February 23 in the Julian calendar).
events.html: • 1917 – International Women's Day protests in Petrograd mark the beginning of the February Revolution (February 23 in the Julian calendar).[17]

events.description: The United States Senate votes to limit filibusters by adopting the cloture rule.
events.html: • 1917 – The United States Senate votes to limit filibusters by adopting the cloture rule.[18]

events.description: Spanish Prime Minister Eduardo Dato Iradier is assassinated while on his way home from the parliament building in Madrid.
events.html: • 1921 – Spanish Prime Minister Eduardo Dato Iradier is assassinated while on his way home from the parliament building in Madrid.[19]

events.description: A mine disaster kills 172 coal miners near Castle Gate, Utah.
events.html: • 1924 – A mine disaster kills 172 coal miners near Castle Gate, Utah.[20]

events.description: Daytona Beach and Road Course holds its first oval stock car race.
events.html: • 1936 – Daytona Beach and Road Course holds its first oval stock car race.[21]

events.description: Spanish Civil War: The Battle of Guadalajara begins.

events.description: World War II: The Dutch East Indies surrender Java to the Imperial Japanese Army.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Dutch East Indies surrender Java to the Imperial Japanese Army.[23]

events.html: • 1942 – World War II: Imperial Japanese Army forces captured Rangoon, Burma from British.[24]

events.description: The iconic Volkswagen Type 2 "Bus" begins production.

events.description: Nelson's Pillar in Dublin, Ireland, is destroyed by a bomb.

events.description: The first Aurat March (social/political demonstration) was held being International Women's Day in Karachi, Pakistan, since then annually held  across Pakistan and feminist slogan Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My body, my choice), in demand for women's right to bodily autonomy and against gender-based violence came into vogue in Pakistan.
events.html: • 2018 – The first Aurat March (social/political demonstration) was held being International Women's Day in Karachi, Pakistan, since then annually held across Pakistan and feminist slogan Mera Jism Meri Marzi (My body, my choice), in demand for women's right to bodily autonomy and against gender-based violence came into vogue in Pakistan.[41][42][43]
